		<body>
			<p rend="align(center)"><placeName>Richmond</placeName> <date>February 28&#44; 1830</date></p>
			<p>My dear <addressee>Isaac</addressee></p>
			<p>I Rd your last letter.  I see the <add>cost&#63;</add> to <sic>printing</sic> your books<lb/> is much more than you wrote to me before as I know you will not<lb/> publish it without some <sic>prosback</sic> of gaining something by it I will<lb/> say nothing now on the subject but I Leave it to your judgement to<lb/> do with it as you please.  I would take 20 or 30 copies of it as so<lb/> soon as they are printed but that would be a poor chance for the<lb/> rest&#44; I wish you could do it with some <sic>ass urance</sic> of gain<lb/> how ever if not at present I am sure&#44; in some short time you may be<lb/> <sic>aboe</sic> to do it to advantage.  I saw <persName>Mr. Mordecai</persName> last week he said<lb/> he would take a Copy but said nothing Else he has not called here<lb/> for 2 Months.  We are all well&#44; hope you are better of your Cold<lb/> no news.</p>
		  <p rend="indent(1)">I remain your <del>fri</del> affectionate <persName role="author">Uncle Zalma Rehina</persName><lb/> Your Aunt &amp; rs e Pass <persName>Reina Abby</persName> and all your friends send<lb/> their love to you.  Remember me kindly to <persName>Mr. &amp; Mrs Piexotto</persName><lb/> and the young laydes and all my friends in <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName></p>
		  <p rend="indent(1)"><persName>Mrs Sol Marks</persName> Desires to be remembered to you</p>
		</body>
